Here is code which catch ineficient parsing for list of strings:

```
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.ObjectMapper
import com.fasterxml.jackson.module.scala.DefaultScalaModule
import com.fasterxml.jackson.module.scala.experimental.ScalaObjectMapper

def performance[R](name: => String, series: Int, times: Long)(f: => R): R = {
  var result: R = null.asInstanceOf[R]
  for (s <- 1 to series) {
    var i = 0
    val t = System.nanoTime()
    while (i < times) {
      result = f
      i += 1
    }
    val d = System.nanoTime() - t
    println(f"$name elapsed: ${d / 1000000} ms, performance: ${times * 1000000000.0 / d}%2.2f op/s")
  }
  result
}

val json = (1 to 1000).map(_.toString).mkString("[\"", "\",\"", "\"]")
val mapper = new ObjectMapper with ScalaObjectMapper {
  registerModule(DefaultScalaModule)
}
val request = performance("parse list of strings", 5, 10000) {
  mapper.readValue[List[String]](json)
}
```

But you are right, that need to check if there are any other posibilities to fix the problem with Scala collections w/o affecting of other users (Java, Kotlin, etc.).

P.S. All is fine for array of strings, when replace `mapper.readValue[List[String]](json)` by `mapper.readValue[Array[String]](json)`

@plokhotnyuk Quick question; you said "40x" slow down, but perhaps you mean "40%" (40 percent)? The reason I am asking is that with a simple java-only test, with a small single-element JSON Array I can get difference of maybe 2.5x, which while big difference isn't quite that drastic. But it is possible there might be something additional that Scala mapper does, to try to carry generic type, above and beyond what `TypeReference` (from Jackson) would do.

Another oddity is that although type resolution was indeed rewritten for 2.7, cost of generic type resolution should not have been negligible even before, so sudden addition seems odd.

How much does caching help, compared to not caching?
